 To deploy a containerized application on AWS ECS, follow these steps using the AWS Cloud Development Kit (AWS CDK):

1. Set up your AWS CDK development environment and install the AWS CDK by running the following command: [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a>]

   ```
   npm init aws-cdk
   cdks init app --language typescript
   npm install
   cdk bootstrap
   ```

2. Create a new stack for your containerized application: [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a> > Step 1: Set up your AWS CDK project<a name="ecs-web-server-cdk-step-1"></a>]

   ```
   cdk create MyEcsStack --template "AWS::CloudFormation::Stack"
   cd MyEcsStack
   ```

3. Define the containerized web server on Fargate in `lib/myecsstack.ts`: [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a> > Step 2: Use the AWS CDK to define a containerized web server on Fargate<a name="ecs-web-server-cdk-step-2"></a>]

   ```typescript
   import * as cdk from '@aws-cdk/core';
   import * as ecs from '@aws-cdk/aws-ecs';
   import * as ecsPatterns from '@aws-cdk/aws-ecs-patterns';

   export class MyEcsStack extends cdk.Stack {
       constructor(scope: cdk.Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
           super(scope, id, props);

           const vpc = ecs.Vpc.fromExistingVpc(this, 'vpc', { vpcId: 'your-existing-vpc-id' });

           const cluster = new ecs.Cluster(this, 'cluster', { clusterName: 'my-ecs-cluster', vpc });

           const service = new ecsPatterns.ApplicationLoadBalancedFargateService(this, 'service', {
               cluster,
               cpu: 256,
               desiredCount: 1,
               taskImageOptions: { image: ecs.ContainerImage.fromRegistry('amazon/amazon-ecs-sample') },
               publicLoadBalancer: true,
           });
       }
   }
   ```

4. Synthesize the AWS CloudFormation template from your app and display it: [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a> > Step 2: Use the AWS CDK to define a containerized web server on Fargate<a name="ecs-web-server-cdk-step-2"></a>]

   ```
   cdk synth
   ```

5. Deploy the service in your AWS account: [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a> > Step 2: Use the AWS CDK to define a containerized web server on Fargate<a name="ecs-web-server-cdk-step-2"></a>]

   ```
   cdk deploy
   ```

 To configure networking for Azure Cosmos DB, follow these steps as outlined in the provided documentation:

1. Increase the number of threads/tasks in your .NET application by creating hundreds of tasks that read from or write to Azure Cosmos DB. [Source: 1]

```csharp
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.Azure.Cosmos;

// ...

var cosmosClient = new CosmosClient(
    "<nosql-account-endpoint>",
    tokenCredential
);

for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
    var task = cosmosClient.CreateContainer("<databaseId>", "<containerId>").ReadAllItemsAsync();
    tasks.Add(task);
}

await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
```

2. Enable accelerated networking on your Azure VM to reduce latency and CPU jitter. [Source: 1]
   - For Windows VMs, follow the instructions provided in the [Windows](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/create-vm-accelerated-networking-powershell) or [Linux](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/create-vm-accelerated-networking-cli) guides.

3. Control over consistency requirements through region exclusion patterns. [Source: 2]
   - Create a CosmosClient instance with the ConnectionMode set to Gateway or Direct (the default).

```csharp
CosmosClient client = new CosmosClient(
    "<nosql-account-endpoint>",
    tokenCredential,
    new CosmosClientOptions { ConnectionMode = ConnectionMode.Gateway } // or ConnectionMode.Direct
);
```

4. Limit ephemeral port exhaustion by configuring the CosmosClientOptions.PortReuseMode property to PrivatePortPool and setting the CosmosClientOptions.IdleTcpConnectionTimeout property as greater than or equal to 10 minutes. [Source: 2]

```csharp
CosmosClientOptions options = new CosmosClientOptions
{
    PortReuseMode = PortReuseMode.PrivatePortPool,
    IdleTcpConnectionTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(12) // recommended values are from 20 minutes to 24 hours
};
CosmosClient client = new CosmosClient(
    "<nosql-account-endpoint>",
    tokenCredential,
    options
);
```

5. For performance, collocate clients in the same Azure region as the Azure Cosmos DB database. [Source: 1]

6. When your function app runs in an App Service plan or an App Service Environment, you can write functions that are triggered by resources secured by a virtual network. To configure Azure Cosmos DB to accept traffic only from a virtual network, deploy your function app in an App Service plan that provides virtual network integration with the virtual network associated with the Azure Cosmos DB resource. [Source: 3]

7. For accounts configured with strong consistency and more than one region, the write latency is equal to two times round-trip time (RTT) between any of the two farthest regions, plus 10 milliseconds at the 99th percentile. To monitor replication latencies between various regions associated with your Azure Cosmos DB account, use the Azure portal by going to the Metrics section and selecting the Consistency option. [Source: 4]

8. To configure a service endpoint by using the Azure CLI, follow the instructions provided in the [Connect and configure an Azure Cosmos DB account to a back-end subnet independently](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/how-to-configure-vnet-service-endpoint#connect-and-configure-an-azure-cosmos-db-account-to-a-backend-subnet-independently) guide. [Source: 5]

 Based on the provided documentation, there are several ways to scale Azure Blob Storage horizontally:

1. **Using Service Endpoint Policies**: This feature allows you to filter Azure service traffic from virtual networks, over service endpoints. It provides a horizontally scalable and highly available solution. Here's how to create a JSON object for Service Endpoint policies:

   [CODE_BLOCK_0]
   {
     "properties": {
       "endpointPolicy": {
         "allowBlobServicePublicAccess": false,
         "enabled": true
       }
     }
   }
   [Source: azure/Virtual Network/Virtual network service endpoint policies for Azure Storage > JSON Object for Service Endpoint policies]

2. **Using Blob Index Tags**: You can use blob index tags to manage and find data on Azure Blob Storage. This can help in scaling by organizing your data more efficiently. Here's how to set index tags on objects at scale across multiple storage accounts:

   - Learn more about blob index tags, see [Manage and find Azure Blob data with blob index tags](storage-manage-find-blobs.md)
   - Learn more about Azure Storage Actions, which can help you set index tags on objects at scale across multiple storage accounts. See [What is Azure Storage Actions?](../../storage-actions/overview.md)

3. **Using Premium Block Blob Storage Accounts**: For applications that cannot scale up by adding more clients, you can use Azure premium block blob storage account. It offers consistent low-latency and high transaction rates. Here's how to create a premium block blob storage account:

   Follow the steps provided in [Azure premium block blob storage account](../common/storage-account-create.md) documentation.
